Inman Elementary School PTO
July 29 at 6:10 PM ¬∑

Good evening IES Parents! I hope you are all doing well! PTO is looking at the possibility of purchasing Teuton Youth Masks for our students. We would sell these to students at cost in order to spread school spirit in a difficult time. The cost would be $5 per mask. If you're interested, please respond to this post. If we have enough interest, we will proceed with purchasing them and share more details later. If you have any questions, feel free to respond to this post, send a FB message, or email me at ieskspto@gmail.com.

Kayla Sawyer
IES PTO President

post_text: One of the many cancellations due to the Covid-19 pandemic was McPherson County's annual May Fete festivities. The May Fete committee wanted to honor the area royalty and have their pictures taken in a formal setting even though the event could not go on. Inman HS was proud to be represented by the members of the royalty court pictured here. King Nicholas Martisko, Queen Rachel Harman, Princess Mackenze Sherrer and Crown Bearer James Colle.

post_text:
Agatha Smyers Scholarship for the Service Professions recipient announced.
The McPherson County Community Foundation is proud to recognize Inman HS alumni, Elizabeth Wood as the 2020 recipient of the Agatha Smyers Scholarship. She will be receiving a $1000 scholarship to continue her education next Fall at Wichita State University where she is
majoring in Nursing.
Graduates of Inman High School who have completed 5 semesters in college and are working
toward a degree in the service industry, which could include: educators, clergy, social services,
registered nursing, physical therapy, physicians or dentists are encouraged to apply for the
Agatha Smyers Scholarship awarded in the spring of each year. #CongratulationsLizWood

shared_text:
2020CENSUS.GOV
2020 Census | United States Census Bureau

McPherson County 911
April 9 at 12:34 PM ¬∑

We'd like to interrupt this pandemic to discuss the 2020 Census. Have you filled yours out yet?

And you're probably saying "Census Shmensus - that does nothing for me...WE'RE IN A PANDEMIC FOR CRYIN' OUT LOUD!"

And I'll say, "Oh yes, I'm so glad you pointed that out."

Because.... the PPE (masks, gloves, and gowns) allotted to our County by FEMA is based off the 2010 Census numbers!!! Our County received .01% of the equipment provided to the state of Kansas. Do your part to help keep the Census accurate for McPherson County for future needs!

Box Tops are no longer the kind that you cut off the box. Instead, you will need to scan your receipt with the Box Top phone app after shopping and the Box Top information is collected digitally. So instead of cutting box tops, it is time to get into the habit of scanning your grocery receipt with the Box Top app on your phone.

Many of us are doing online grocery shopping, but you can simply forward your email receipt to receipts@boxtops4education.com and the information will be collected for our school. This month we had zero earnings. For the school year we have had $426.20 in earnings. This is an easy way for you to support our school. Please download the Box Top App today and help support Inman Elementary School. https://www.boxtops4education.com/

post_text:
Updated information
KSDE is recommending that all schools close for the week of March 16-20. Since we are on Spring Break during the upcoming week, we were not planning on classes being held during this time. There has not been a decision made about whether or not schools will open the week after March 16-20. That decision will be made later this week. Since schools are closed this week, there will not be any activity practices March 16-22. A final decision from KSHSAA on the spring sport season has not been made at this time. The Wellness Center will also be closed. Key card access will not be available.

post_text:
On Tuesday, March 10th, the JH Choir & Band traveled to Trinity to participate in the HOA League Music Festival. The students represented Inman very well. Students receiving a 1-Superior on their vocal solo (photo 1) were: Aaron Bartel, Kendal Brueggen, Alexis Hase, Madilyn Heflin, David Knetchel, Brylee Mannebach, and Nathan Reinecker. The 8th Grade Ladies Trio (photo 2), consisting of Brylee, Madi and Lexi, received a 1-Superior on their song and the 7th/8th Grade Ladies Small Ensemble (photo 3) also got a 1-Superior on their song.
The JH Choir received a combined score of a II+ - Excellent.
Great job Guys and Gals!

post_text:
Justin Schroeder Signs with Bethany College

Justin Schroeder, senior at Inman High School has signed a letter of intent to play football at Bethany College next fall. Justin is the son of Kevin Schroeder and Angela Young.

Pictured from L. ‚Äì R.
Front Row ‚Äì Angela Young, Justin Schroeder, and Kevin Schroeder
Back Row ‚Äì Inman Assistant Bill Garst, Inman Head Coach Lance Sawyer, Inman Assistant Greg Froese, and Bethany head Coach Curren White.

Some Defensive Stats from his senior year:

101 tackles ‚Äì 20 solo and 81 assisted
1 sack
7 tackles for loss
1 forced fumble

Justin plans on majoring in Business at Bethany. His goal is to have his own Mechanics Shop.

shared_text:
McPherson College
March 3 at 4:00 PM ¬∑

Two excellent opportunities to support music at MC happen to fall on the same day ‚Äì Sunday, March 8!

Enjoy the Collaborative Choir Concert with Inman Schools high school choir at 2:30 p.m. in the McPherson Church of the Brethren. Alumna Staci Horton directs the Inman choir. Both the MC and Inman choir will sing selections and then will perform ‚ÄúBridge Over Troubled Water‚Äù and ‚ÄúBe Ye Glad‚Äù together.

The Collaborative Band Concert with Hutchinson Community College will be in Brown Auditorium at 6 p.m. A highlight includes the MC band will performing "The Sisu Within You" by Meri Jenkins, a piece composed specifically for the band.

Join us!

Statement from the district about the Novel Coronavirus

Keeping our schools safe and healthy is one of the main goals for USD 448. We are working closely with the McPherson County Health Department and KDHE to stay informed about the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19). Currently there are NO confirmed cases in Kansas.

Here are some general recommendations to help prevent the spread of any respiratory virus, including the Novel Coronavirus:
Wash hands frequently with soap and water. Hand sanitizer is ok if soap and water is not available.
Wipe down frequently touched surfaces (computer mouse, cell phone, door handles, etc..)
Stay home if you aren‚Äôt feeling well
Avoid those who are sick
Stay healthy-eat well, get plenty of sleep, & stay hydrated.

For more information you can visit the CDC website, https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html, or contact the McPherson County Health Department at https://www.mcphersoncountyks.us/15/Health-Department

post_text: Enjoy this week's #HSTeutonTakeover: ‚ÄúI am Johannes Andreasen and I am a foreign exchange student at Inman High School. Since I could choose the classes I wanted myself, I have a lot of Mr. Cearly‚Äôs classes and it is great. My day includes English II, Health/PE, Government, 21st Century Journalism, American History, Personal Finance, and Spanish I. I played football most of the first semester and I am currently playing basketball, and I look forward to trying baseball. After high school in America, I will go back to Denmark and go to high school there, with more cultural knowledge‚Äù.

post_text:
Happy Valentines Day!

Sophomore Tristen Witt won the STUCO sponsored Valentines Day Guessing Game. He guessed 746 pieces of candy and there were 777 in the jar. Joining Tristen in the photo are Stuco President Rachel Harman and Vice President Nicholas Martisko.

Second and third place winners were sophomore Caleb Enz, and sophomore Hannah Martisko. STUCO wants to thank everyone for participating. Winner Tristen dedicated the jar of candy to Mrs. Ryan's classroom to share with his fellow classmates.

post_text: For this week's #HSTeutonTakeover we have Mason Carter, and he is in the Junior class. ‚ÄúMy first three hours are the hardest of the day.‚Äù These include American History, Advanced Math, and English. ‚ÄúAfter lunch, I go to Art for the next two hours, and then to fitness.‚Äù Mason‚Äôs favorite class is fitness because he finds it relaxing. ‚ÄúAfter that, I go to physics, which is my last hour.‚Äù Mason is also involved in football and basketball, he says as of right now his favorite sport is basketball and he can always look forward to it throughout the day. Interview by Jayden Leonhardt (11th).

post_text: January 29th is approaching fast and we are very excited to have Inman HS alumnus Marci Penner come and share with us. Marci and her co-author WenDee Rowe, will be sharing some of what went into creating the book 'Kansas Guidebook 2 for Explorers'. The book has 4,500 entries and more than 1,600 pictures. The entries feature 515 incorporated cities in all 105 counties and 97 unincorporated spots in the road. Both Marci and WenDee come to us from the Kansas Sampler Foundation

What a beautiful piece! #MaximizingStudentResources #DriveStudentSuccess

post_text:
Congratulations to NICHOLAS MARTISKO for receiving the Kansas Cross Country and Track & Field Class 2A Cross Country Academic All-State Team!

To qualify for the award, applicants must:
- Be a junior or senior
- Have an unweighted GPA of 3.75 or higher
- Place in the top 30 at this year's state cross country meet
- Receive a nomination from their high school coach

Due to Nick meeting and exceeding all of these qualifications (with his 3.94 GPA and 3rd place finish at State), Mr. Parsons was proud to present him with this honor on January 10.

post_text: Carolyn Devane, Director and instructor of ACT PowerPrep is at Inman HS today working with 19 students on improving their test taking skills. Carolyn is out of the Manhattan area and does workshops all over the state of Kansas for high school students who are preparing for the ACT and trying to raise their score. The four hour session is very challenging and mentally exhausting for students but the Inman alum who have taken this workshop with Carolyn have had nothing but praise for her and how she has helped them. Students taking this workshop usually end up raising their score on the ACT with the test taking advice Carolyn shares. Inman HS is thankful to be able to offer this workshop to students who are wanting to improve.

post_text:
Inman High School students were fortunate to have seven alumni from the class of 2019 come back today and share what their experience in college has been like so far. The alumni shared some very valuable information and advice to those students who plan to go on to college. Many themes surfaced today as we listened to the alumni share: advice on developing good study habits, preparing for tests, focus on not procrastinating, developing good time management skills and being willing to work hard were all traits that seemed to be stressed. One of the comments that really hit home from the alumni was when Macy shared that ‚Äúin High school you want to graduate, get out of Inman and then as soon as you go somewhere else you realize how amazing our community is, enjoy it.‚Äù The full question and answer session can be seen on the USD 448 Facebook page.

Bailey Eck (KSU), Damion Raney (Pitt St.) Reagen Snow (HCC), Koy Light (WSU), Macy DeWitt (Fort Hays State), Michael Bledsoe (HCC) and Mason Thiessen (Emporia State).
